Modifications for monkey-skills dev-workflow plugin
---------------------------------------------------

The following changes were made to adapt the upstream skill to the
monkey-skills repository conventions. None of the upstream's evaluation
content (D1-D8 rubric, philosophy, protocol, output format, failure
patterns) has been altered.

1. Frontmatter rewritten to match dev-workflow plugin's frontmatter
   convention (explicit `Use when` / `Do NOT use for` / `Delivers`
   clauses, multi-language keyword tail line for trigger discovery).
   The new description references sibling skills:
     - `dev-workflow:skill-creator-advance` (behavioral / runtime eval)
     - `domain-teams:skill-team` (domain-team convention enforcement)
   to clarify scope boundaries.

2. New section "Adaptation for monkey-skills domain-team skills"
   inserted before "The Meta-Question". Establishes the core
   principle that skill-judge is advisory (0-120 design-quality
   scoring) and `domain-teams:skill-team`'s gates are authoritative
   (PASS/FAIL convention enforcement) — gate failures surface as
   "Critical Issues" in the report without capping D1-D8 scores.
   Provides:
     - D7 clarification (domain-team skills fit upstream Process
       pattern by structural characteristics; line count is a
       correlate, not the criterion; report Pattern field = `Process`)
     - D4 supplementary check (run CHK-SKL-001 in addition to
       WHAT/WHEN/KEYWORDS; failure → Critical Issue, no score cap)
     - D5 supplementary check (run CHK-SKL-010 token cap; failure
       → Critical Issue, no score cap; Dump pattern penalized
       separately per upstream criteria)
     - Focus-dimension guidance (D1/D3/D6 carry the most net-new
       value above what skill-team gates partially cover for
       D4/D5/D8)
     - Explicit "complementary, not replacement" statement vs
       skill-team gates with both-pass/both-fail examples.

3. Inline note added at the end of D7 cross-referencing the new
   adaptation section. Notes that domain-team skills fit Process
   pattern structurally despite exceeding upstream's typical line
   count for that pattern.

4. License block: dual-copyright header preserving Leonardo Flores's
   2026 copyright (upstream) plus 2026 kouko (modifications).

